<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-496-992  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 496 992.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 25 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Singapore giving 10,000 computer training.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Worsley, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SingaporeComputer industryTraining of EmployeesGovernment Contracts.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>SINGAPORE GIVING 10,000 COMPUTER TRAINING SINGAPORE, S.E.andP;  ASIA, 1989 JUL 11(NB) -- The government plans to train at least 10,000 clerks and secretariesin the use of personal computers by the end of this year as part of itsefforts to improve office productivity.andP;  The Information Technology (IT)Programme for Office Workers was set up jointly last year by the NationalProductivity Board (NPB) and IBM, the first such venture between the NPB anda private company for training on a national basis.andP;  About 3,900 officeworkers from more than 800 companies covering a wide cross-section ofindustry have so far been trained under the scheme.andP;  The country's SkillsDevelopment Fund, which subsidizes 70 percent of costs or S$560 (US$300) pertrainee, has, to date, spent S$2.3 million (US$1.25 million) on theprogramme.andP;  The NPB also set up the Festo-NPB Industrial Training Centrejointly with a German industrial automation company Festo to provide basicautomation skills training for about 20,000 production workers, machinistsand assemblers over the next five years.andP;  Minister of State Mah Bow Tan saidat the opening of this centre, &quot;Industry has found this computer and officeautomation training programme a valuable resource to harness, in upgradingthe skills of their workforce.&quot; (Michael Worsley andamp; S.Roowi/19890718)</TEXT></DOC>